10242750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==== Dutch origins ====@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10242760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Words describing the navy, types of ships, and other objects or activities on the water are often from Dutch origin.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10242770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Yacht'' (''jacht'') and ''cruiser'' (''kruiser'') are examples.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10242780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==== French origins ====@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10242790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are many [[List of English words of French origin|words of French origin in English]], such as ''competition'', ''art'', ''table'', ''publicity'', ''police'', ''role'', ''routine'', ''machine'', ''force'', and many others that have been and are being [[anglicisation|anglicised]]; they are now pronounced according to English rules of [[phonology]], rather than French.@1@49@@oe@30-11-2008
10242800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A large portion of English vocabulary is of French or [[Langues d'oïl]] origin, most derived from, or transmitted via, the [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-Norman]] spoken by the [[upper class]]es in [[England]] for several hundred years after the [[Norman conquest of England]].@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10242810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Writing system ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10242820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@English has been written using the [[Latin alphabet]] since around the ninth century.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10242830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(Before that, Old English had been written using [[Anglo-Saxon runes]].)@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10242840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The spelling system, or [[orthography]], is multilayered, with elements of French, Latin and Greek spelling on top of the native Germanic system; it has grown to vary significantly from the [[phonology]] of the language.@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10242850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The spelling of words often diverges considerably from how they are spoken.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10242860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Though letters and sounds may not correspond in isolation, spelling rules that take into account syllable structure, phonetics, and accents are 75% or more reliable.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10242870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some phonics spelling advocates claim that English is more than 80% phonetic.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10242880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In general, [[history of the English language|the English language]], being the product of many other languages and having only been codified orthographically in the 16th century, has fewer consistent relationships between sounds and letters than many other languages.@1@38@@oe@30-11-2008
10242890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The consequence of this orthographic history is that reading can be challenging.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10242900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It takes longer for students to become completely fluent readers of English than of many other languages, including French, Greek, and Spanish.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10242910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Basic sound-letter correspondence ===@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10242920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Only the consonant letters are pronounced in a relatively regular way:@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10242930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Written accents ===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10242940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Unlike most other Germanic languages, English has almost no [[diacritic]]s except in foreign [[loanword]]s (like the [[acute accent]] in ''café''), and in the uncommon use of a [[diaeresis]] mark (often in formal writing) to indicate that two vowels are pronounced separately, rather than as one sound (e.g. ''naïve, Zoë'').@1@49@@oe@30-11-2008
10242950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is almost always acceptable to leave out the marks, especially in digital communications where the [[QWERTY]] keyboard lacks any marked letters, but it depends on the context where the word is used.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10242960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some English words retain the diacritic to distinguish them from others, such as ''[[Animé (oleo-resin)|animé]], [[Investigative journalism|exposé]], [[Lamé (fencing)|lamé]], [[öre]], [[øre]], [[pâté]], [[piqué]],'' and ''[[rosé]]'', though these are sometimes also dropped (''[[résumé]]/resumé'' is usually spelled ''resume'' in the United States).@1@40@@oe@30-11-2008
10242970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are loan words which occasionally use a diacritic to represent their pronunciation that is not in the original word, such as ''maté'', from Spanish ''[[yerba mate]]'', following the French usage, but they are extremely rare.@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10242980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Formal written English ==@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10242990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A version of the language almost universally agreed upon by educated English speakers around the world is called [[formal written English]].@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10243000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It takes virtually the same form no matter where in the English-speaking world it is written.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10243010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In spoken English, by contrast, there are a vast number of differences between [[dialect]]s, [[Accent (linguistics)|accents]], and varieties of [[slang]], colloquial and regional expressions.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10243020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In spite of this, local variations in the formal written version of the language are quite limited, being restricted largely to the [[American and British English spelling differences|spelling differences between British and American English]].@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10243030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Basic and simplified versions ==@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10243040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@To make English easier to read, there are some simplified versions of the language.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10243050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@One basic version is named ''[[Basic English]]'', a [[constructed language]] with a small number of words created by [[Charles Kay Ogden]] and described in his book ''Basic English: A General Introduction with Rules and Grammar'' (1930).@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10243060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The language is based on a simplified version of English.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10243070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Ogden said that it would take seven years to learn English, seven months for [[Esperanto]], and seven weeks for Basic English, comparable with [[Ido]].@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10243080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus Basic English is used by companies who need to make complex books for international use, and by language schools that need to give people some knowledge of English in a short time.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10243090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Ogden did not put any words into Basic English that could be said with a few other words and he worked to make the words work for speakers of any other language.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10243100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@He put his set of words through a large number of tests and adjustments.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10243110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@He also made the grammar simpler, but tried to keep the grammar normal for English users.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10243120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The concept gained its greatest publicity just after the [[World War II|Second World War]] as a tool for world peace.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10243130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Although it was not built into a program, similar simplifications were devised for various international uses.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10243140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another version, [[Simplified English]], exists, which is a [[Controlled natural language|controlled language]] originally developed for [[aerospace]] industry maintenance manuals.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10243150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It offers a carefully limited and standardised subset of English.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10243160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Simplified English has a lexicon of approved words and those words can only be used in certain ways.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10243170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, the word ''close'' can be used in the phrase "Close the door" but not "do not go close to the landing gear".@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10250010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>Esperanto</article>@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10250020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@is by far the most widely spoken [[constructed language|constructed]] [[international auxiliary language]] in the world.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10250030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Its name derives from ''Doktoro Esperanto,'' the [[pseudonym]] under which [[L. L. Zamenhof]] published the first book detailing Esperanto, the ''[[Unua Libro]],'' in 1887.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10250040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The word ''esperanto'' means 'one who hopes' in the language itself.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10250050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Zamenhof's goal was to create an easy and flexible language that would serve as a universal [[second language]] to foster peace and international understanding.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10250060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto has had continuous usage by a community estimated at between 100,000 and 2 million speakers for over a century.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10250070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@By most estimates, there are approximately one thousand [[Native Esperanto speakers|native speakers]].@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10250080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, no country has adopted the language [[official language|officially]].@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10250090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Today, Esperanto is employed in world travel, correspondence, cultural exchange, conventions, literature, language instruction, television, and radio broadcasting.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10250100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Also, there is an [[Esperanto Wikipedia]] that contains over 100,000 articles as of June 2008.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10250110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There is evidence that [[Propaedeutic value of Esperanto|learning Esperanto may provide a good foundation for learning languages in general]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10250120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some state education systems offer basic instruction and elective courses in Esperanto.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10250130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto is also the language of instruction in one university, the [[Akademio Internacia de la Sciencoj San Marino|Akademio Internacia de la Sciencoj]] in [[San Marino]].@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10250140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== History ==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10250150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto was developed in the late 1870s and early 1880s by [[ophthalmology|ophthalmologist]] [[L. L. Zamenhof|Dr. Ludovic Lazarus Zamenhof]], an [[Ashkenazi Jew]] from [[Bialystok]], now in [[Poland]] and previously in the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]], but at the time part of the [[Russian Empire]].@1@41@@oe@30-11-2008
10250160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@After some ten years of development, which Zamenhof spent translating literature into the language as well as writing original [[prose]] and [[Poetry|verse]], the [[Unua Libro|first book of Esperanto grammar]] was published in [[Warsaw]] in July 1887.@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10250170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The number of speakers grew rapidly over the next few decades, at first primarily in the [[Russian empire]] and [[Eastern Europe]], then in [[Western Europe]], the [[Americas]], [[China]], and [[Japan]].@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10250180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the early years, speakers of Esperanto kept in contact primarily through correspondence and [[magazine|periodicals]], but in 1905 the first [[World Congress of Esperanto|world congress of Esperanto speakers]] was held in [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]], [[France]].@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10250190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Since then world congresses have been held in different countries every year, except during the two [[world war|World Wars]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10250200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Since the Second World War, they have been attended by an average of over 2000 and up to 6000 people.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10250210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Relation to 20th-century totalitarianism===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10250220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As a potential vehicle for international understanding, Esperanto attracted the suspicion of many [[totalitarian]] states.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10250230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The situation was especially pronounced in [[Nazi Germany]] and in the [[Soviet Union]] under [[Joseph Stalin]].@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10250240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In Germany, there was additional motivation to persecute Esperanto because Zamenhof was a Jew.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10250250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In his work ''[[Mein Kampf]],'' [[Hitler]] mentioned Esperanto as an example of a language that would be used by an [[International Jewry|International]] [[Jewish conspiracy|Jewish Conspiracy]] once they achieved [[world domination]].@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10250260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Esperantist]]s were executed during [[the Holocaust]], with Zamenhof's family in particular singled out for execution.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10250270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the early years of the Soviet Union, Esperanto was given a measure of government support, and an officially recognized Soviet Esperanto Association came into being.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10250280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, in 1937, Stalin reversed this policy.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10250290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@He denounced Esperanto as "the language of spies" and had Esperantists executed.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10250300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The use of Esperanto remained illegal until 1956.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10250310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Official use==@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10250320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto has never been an official language of any recognized country.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10250330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, there were plans at the beginning of the 20th century to establish [[Moresnet|Neutral Moresnet]] as the world's first Esperanto state.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10250340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In China, there was talk in some circles after the 1911 [[Xinhai Revolution]] about officially replacing [[Chinese language|Chinese]] with Esperanto as a means to dramatically bring the country into the twentieth century, though this policy proved untenable.@1@37@@oe@30-11-2008
10250350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the summer of 1924, the [[American Radio Relay League]] adopted Esperanto as its official [[international auxiliary language]], and hoped that the language would be used by [[Amateur radio|radio amateurs]] in international communications, but its actual use for radio communications was negligible.@1@42@@oe@30-11-2008
10250360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In addition, the self-proclaimed [[artificial island]] [[micronation]] of [[Republic of Rose Island|Rose Island]] used Esperanto as its official language in 1968.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10250370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto is the working language of several [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] international organizations such as the ''[[Sennacieca Asocio Tutmonda]]'', but most others are specifically Esperanto organizations.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10250380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The largest of these, the [[World Esperanto Association]], has an official consultative relationship with the [[United Nations]] and [[UNESCO]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10250390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The U.S. Army has published military phrasebooks in Esperanto, to be used in [[Military simulation|wargames]] by mock enemy forces.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10250400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto is also the first language of teaching and administration of the [[Akademio Internacia de la Sciencoj San Marino|International Academy of Sciences San Marino]], which is sometimes called an "Esperanto University".@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10250410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Linguistic properties ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10250420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Classification ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10250430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As a [[constructed language]], Esperanto is not [[Genealogy|genealogically]] related to any [[ethnic group|ethnic]] language.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10250440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It has been described as "a language [[lexicon|lexically]] predominantly [[Romance languages|Romanic]], [[morphology (linguistics)|morphologically]] intensively [[agglutination|agglutinative]] and to a certain degree [[isolating languages|isolating]] in character".@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10250450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[phonology]], [[grammar]], [[vocabulary]], and [[semantics]] are based on the western [[Indo-European languages]].@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10250460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[phoneme|phonemic inventory]] is essentially [[Slavic languages|Slavic]], as is much of the semantics, while the [[vocabulary]] derives primarily from the [[Romance languages]], with a lesser contribution from the [[Germanic languages]].@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10250470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Pragmatics]] and other aspects of the language not specified by Zamenhof's original documents were influenced by the native languages of early speakers, primarily [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Polish language|Polish]], [[German language|German]], and [[French language|French]].@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10250480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Linguistic typology|Typologically]], Esperanto has [[preposition]]s and a [[information flow|pragmatic word order]] that by default is ''[[Subject Verb Object]]'' and ''[[Word order|Adjective Noun]]''.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10250490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@New words are formed through extensive [[prefix (linguistics)|prefix]]ing and [[suffix]]ing.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10250500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Writing system ===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10250510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto is written with a modified version of the [[Latin alphabet]], including six [[Letter (alphabet)|letters]] with [[diacritic]]s: [[c-circumflex|ĉ]], [[g-circumflex|ĝ]], [[h-circumflex|ĥ]], [[j-circumflex|ĵ]], [[s-circumflex|ŝ]] and [[u-breve|ŭ]] (that is, ''c, g, h, j, s'' [[circumflex]], and ''u'' [[breve]]).@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10250520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The alphabet does not include the letters ''q, w, x,'' or ''y'' except in unassimilated foreign names.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10250530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The 28-letter alphabet is: <big><center>'''a b c ĉ d e f g ĝ h ĥ i j ĵ k l m n o p r s ŝ t u ŭ v z'''</center></big>@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10250540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@All letters are pronounced approximately as in the [[IPA]], with the exception of ''c'' and the accented letters:@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10250550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Two [[ASCII]]-compatible writing conventions are in use.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10250560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These substitute [[Digraph (orthography)|digraph]]s for the accented letters.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10250570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The original "h-convention" (''ch, gh, hh, jh, sh, u'') is based on English 'ch' and 'sh', while a more recent "[[x-convention]]" (''cx, gx, hx, jx, sx, ux'') is useful for alphabetic word sorting on a [[computer]] (''cx'' comes correctly after ''cu'', ''sx'' after ''sv'', etc.) as well as for simple conversion back into the standard [[orthography]].@1@56@@oe@30-11-2008
10250580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another scheme represents the superscripted letters by a [[caret]] (^), as for example: c^ or ^c.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10250590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Phonology ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10250600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:''(For help with the phonetic symbols, see [[Help:IPA]])''@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10250610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto has 22 [[consonant]]s, 5 [[vowel]]s, and two [[semivowel]]s, which combine with the vowels to form 6 [[diphthong]]s.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10250620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(The consonant {{IPA|/j/}} and semivowel {{IPA|/i̯/}} are both written <j>.) [[tone (linguistics)|Tone]] is not used to distinguish meanings of words.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10250630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Stress (linguistics)|Stress]] is always on the penultimate vowel, unless a final vowel ''o'' is [[Elision|elided]], a practice which occurs mostly in [[poetry]].@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10250640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, ''familio'' "family" is stressed {{IPA2|fa.mi.ˈli.o}}, but when found without the final o, ''famili’,'' the stress does not shift: {{IPA|[fa.mi.ˈli]}}.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10250650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==== Consonants ====@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10250660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The 22 consonants are:@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10250670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The sound {{IPA|/r/}} is usually [[alveolar trill|rolled]], but may be [[alveolar flap|tapped]] {{IPA|[ɾ]}}.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10250680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The {{IPA|/v/}} has a normative pronunciation like an [[English language|English]] ''v,'' but is sometimes somewhere between a ''v'' and a ''w,'' {{IPA|[ʋ]}}, depending on the language background of the speaker.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10250690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A semivowel {{IPA|/u̯/}} normally occurs only in [[diphthong]]s after the vowels {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/e/}}, not as a consonant {{IPA|*/w/}}.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10250700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Common, if debated, [[assimilation (linguistics)|assimilation]] includes the pronunciation of {{IPA|/nk/}} as {{IPA|[ŋk]}}, as in English ''sink,'' and {{IPA|/kz/}} as {{IPA|[gz]}}, like the ''x'' in English ''example''.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10250710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A large number of consonant clusters can occur, up to three in initial position and four in medial position, as in ''instrui'' "to teach".@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10250720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Final clusters are uncommon except in foreign names, poetic elision of final ''o,'' and a very few basic words such as ''cent'' "hundred" and ''post'' "after".@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10250730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Vowels====@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10250740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto has the five [[cardinal vowels]] of [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Swahili language|Swahili]], and [[Modern Greek]].@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10250750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are six falling diphthongs: ''uj, oj, ej, aj, aŭ, eŭ'' ({{IPA|/ui̯, oi̯, ei̯, ai̯, au̯, eu̯/}}).@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10250760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@With only five vowels, a good deal of variation is tolerated.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10250770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For instance, {{IPA|/e/}} commonly ranges from {{IPA|[e]}} (French ''é'') to {{IPA|[ɛ]}} (French ''è'').@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10250780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The details often depend on the speaker's native language.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10250790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A [[glottal stop]] may occur between adjacent vowels in some people's speech, especially when the two vowels are the same, as in ''heroo'' "hero" ({{IPA|[he.ˈro.o]}} or {{IPA|[he.ˈro.ʔo]}}) and ''praavo'' "great-grandfather" ({{IPA|[pra.ˈa.vo]}} or {{IPA|[pra.ˈʔa.vo]}}).@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10250800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Grammar ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10250810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Esperanto words are [[Derivation (linguistics)|derived]] by stringing together [[prefix (linguistics)|prefix]]es, [[Root (linguistics)|roots]], and [[suffix]]es.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10250820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This process is regular, so that people can create new words as they speak and be understood.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10250830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Compound (linguistics)|Compound]] words are formed with a modifier-first, [[head (linguistics)|head-final]] order, the same order as English "birdsong" ''vs.'' "songbird".@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10250840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The different [[Part of speech|parts of speech]] are marked by their own suffixes: all [[common noun]]s end in ''-o,'' all [[adjective]]s in ''-a,'' all derived adverbs in ''-e,'' and all [[verb]]s in one of six [[Grammatical tense|tense]] and [[Grammatical mood|mood]] suffixes, such as [[present tense]] ''-as.''@1@46@@oe@30-11-2008
10250850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Grammatical number|Plural]] nouns end in ''-oj'' (pronounced "oy"), whereas [[direct object]]s end in ''-on.''@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10250860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Plural direct objects end with the combination ''-ojn'' (pronounced to rhyme with "coin"): That is, ''-o'' for a noun, plus ''-j'' for plural, plus ''-n'' for direct object.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10250870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Adjectives [[Grammatical number#Effect of number on verbs and other parts of speech|agree]] with their nouns; their endings are plural ''-aj'' (pronounced "eye"), direct-object ''-an,'' and plural direct-object ''-ajn'' (pronounced to rhyme with "fine").@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10250880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The suffix ''-n'' is used to indicate the goal of movement and a few other things, in addition to the direct object.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10250890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@See [[Esperanto grammar]] for details.@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10250900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The six verb [[inflection]]s consist of three tenses and three moods.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10250910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They are [[present tense]] ''-as,'' [[future tense]] ''-os,'' [[past tense]] ''-is,'' [[infinitive|infinitive mood]] ''-i,'' [[conditional mood]] ''-us,'' and [[jussive mood]] ''-u'' (used for wishes and commands).@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10250920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Verbs are not marked for person or number.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10250930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For instance: ''kanti'' "to sing"; ''mi kantas'' "I sing"; ''mi kantis'' "I sang"; ''mi kantos'' "I will sing"; ''li kantas'' "he sings"; ''vi kantas'' "you sing".@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10250940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Word order is comparatively free: Adjectives may precede or follow nouns, and subjects, verbs and objects (marked by the suffix ''-n)'' may occur in any order.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10250950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, the [[article (grammar)|article]] ''la'' "the" and [[demonstrative]]s such as ''tiu'' "this, that" almost always come before the noun, and a [[preposition]] such as ''ĉe'' "at" ''must'' come before it.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10250960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Similarly, the negative ''ne'' "not" and [[conjunction]]s such as ''kaj'' "both, and" and ''ke'' "that" must precede the [[phrase]] or [[clause]] they introduce.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10250970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[copula]]r (A = B) clauses, word order is just as important as it is in English clauses like "people are dogs" ''vs.'' "dogs are people".@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10250980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Correlatives====@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10250990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A [[correlative]] is a word used to ask or answer a question of who, where, what, when, or how.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10251000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Correlatives in Esperanto are set out in a systematic manner that correlates a basic [[idea]] (quantity, manner, time, ''etc.'') to a function (questioning, indicating, negating, ''etc.'')@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10251010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples:@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10251020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*''Kio estas tio?''@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10251030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@"What is this?"@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10251040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*''Kioma estas la horo?''@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10251050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@"What time is it?"@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10251060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Note ''kioma'' rather than ''Kiu estas la horo?'' "which is the hour?", when asking for the ranking order of the hour on the clock.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10251070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*''Io falis el la ŝranko'' "Something fell out of the cupboard."@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10251080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*''Homoj tiaj kiel mi ne konadas timon.''@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10251090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@"Men such as me know no fear."@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10251100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Correlatives are declined if the case demands it:@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10251110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*''Vi devas elekti ian vorton pli simpla'' "You should choose a (some kind of) simpler word."@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10251120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Ia'' receives ''-n'' because it's part of the [[direct object]].@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10251130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*''Kian libron vi volas?''@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10251140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@"What sort of book do you want?"@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10251150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Contrast this with, ''Kiun libron vi volas?''@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10251160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@"Which book do you want?"@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10251170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Vocabulary ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10251180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The core vocabulary of Esperanto was defined by ''Lingvo internacia'', published by Zamenhof in 1887.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10251190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It comprised 900 roots, which could be expanded into tens of thousands of words with prefixes, suffixes, and compounding.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10251200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In 1894, Zamenhof published the first Esperanto [[dictionary]], ''Universala Vortaro'', with a larger set of roots.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10251210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, the rules of the language allowed speakers to borrow new roots as needed, recommending only that they look for the most international forms, and then derive related meanings from these.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10251220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Since then, many words have been borrowed, primarily but not solely from the Western European languages.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10251230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Not all proposed borrowings catch on, but many do, especially [[technical terminology|technical]] and [[science|scientific]] terms.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10251240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Terms for everyday use, on the other hand, are more likely to be derived from existing roots—for example ''komputilo'' (a computer) from ''komputi'' (to compute) plus the suffix ''-ilo'' (tool)—or to be covered by extending the meanings of existing words (for example ''muso'' (a mouse), as in English, now also means a computer input device).@1@55@@oe@30-11-2008
10251250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are frequent debates among Esperanto speakers about whether a particular borrowing is justified or whether the need can be met by deriving from or extending the meaning of existing words.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10251260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In addition to the root words and the rules for combining them, a learner of Esperanto must memorize some idiomatic compounds that are not entirely straightforward.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10251270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, ''eldoni'', literally "to give out", is used for "to publish" (a [[calque]] of words in several European languages with the same derivation), and ''vortaro'', literally "a collection of words", means "a glossary" or "a dictionary".@1@37@@oe@30-11-2008
10251280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Such forms are modeled after usage in some European languages, and speakers of other languages may find them illogical.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10251290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Fossilized derivations inherited from Esperanto's source languages may be similarly obscure, such as the opaque connection the root word ''centralo'' "power station" has with ''centro'' "center".@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10251300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Compounds with ''-um-'' are overtly arbitrary, and must be learned individually, as ''-um-'' has no defined meaning.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10251310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It turns ''dekstren'' "to the right" into ''dekstrumen'' "clockwise", and ''komuna'' "common/shared" into ''komunumo'' "community", for example.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10251320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Nevertheless, there are not nearly as many idiomatic or [[slang]] words in Esperanto as in ethnic languages, as these tend to make international communication difficult, working against Esperanto's main goal.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10251330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Useful phrases===@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10251340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Here are some useful Esperanto phrases, with [[help:IPA|IPA]] transcriptions:@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
