10270940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Free software licenses ==@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10270950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@All free software licenses must grant people all the freedoms discussed above.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10270960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, unless the applications' licenses are compatible, combining programs by mixing source code or directly linking binaries is problematic, because of license technicalities.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10270970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Programs indirectly connected together may avoid this problem.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10270980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The majority of free software uses a small set of licenses.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10270990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The most popular of these licenses are:@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10271000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* the [[GNU General Public License]]@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10271010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* the [[GNU Lesser General Public License]]@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10271020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* the [[BSD License]]@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10271030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* the [[Mozilla Public License]]@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10271040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* the [[MIT License]]@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10271050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* the [[Apache License]]@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10271060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The Free Software Foundation and the Open Source Initiative both publish lists of licenses that they find to comply with their own definitions of free software and open-source software respectively.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10271070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[List of FSF approved software licenses]]@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10271080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[List of OSI approved software licenses]]@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10271090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These lists are necessarily incomplete, because a license need not be known by either organization in order to provide these freedoms.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10271100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Apart from these two organizations, the [[Debian]] project is seen by some to provide useful advice on whether particular licenses comply with their [[Debian Free Software Guidelines]].@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10271110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Debian doesn't publish a list of ''approved'' licenses, so its judgments have to be tracked by checking what software they have allowed into their software archives.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10271120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@That is summarized at the Debian web site.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10271130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, it is rare that a license is announced as being in-compliance by either FSF or OSI guidelines and not [[Vice_versa##vice_versa|vice versa]] (the [[Netscape Public License]] used for early versions of Mozilla being an exception), so exact definitions of the terms have not become hot issues.@1@46@@oe@30-11-2008
10271140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Permissive and copyleft licenses ===@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10271150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The FSF categorizes licenses in the following ways:@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10271160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Public domain]] software - the copyright has expired, the work was not copyrighted or the author has abandoned the copyright.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10271170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Since public-domain software lacks copyright protection, it may be freely incorporated into any work, whether proprietary or free.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10271180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[permissive free software licences|Permissive licenses]], also called BSD-style because they are applied to much of the software distributed with the [[Berkeley Software Distribution|BSD]] operating systems.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10271190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The author retains copyright solely to disclaim warranty and require proper attribution of modified works, but permits redistribution and modification in ''any'' work, even proprietary ones.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10271200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Copyleft]] licenses, the [[GNU General Public License]] being the most prominent.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10271210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The author retains copyright and permits redistribution and modification provided all such redistribution is licensed under the same license.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10271220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Additions and modifications by others must also be licensed under the same 'copyleft' license whenever they are distributed with part of the original licensed product.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10271230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Security and reliability==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10271240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There is debate over the [[computer security|security]] of free software in comparison to proprietary software, with a major issue being [[security through obscurity]].@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10271250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A popular quantitative test in computer security is using relative counting of known unpatched security flaws.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10271260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Generally, users of this method advise avoiding products which lack fixes for known security flaws, at least until a fix is available.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10271270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some claim that this method is biased by counting more vulnerabilities for the free software, since its source code is accessible and its community is more forthcoming about what problems exist.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10271280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Free software advocates rebut that even if proprietary software does not have "published" flaws, flaws could still exist and possibly be known to malicious users.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10271290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The ability of users to view and modify the source code allows many more people to potentially analyse the code and possibly to have a higher rate of finding bugs and flaws than an average sized corporation could manage.@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10271300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Users having access to the source code also makes creating and deploying [[spyware]] far more difficult.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10271310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[David A. Wheeler]] has published research concluding that free software is quantitatively more reliable than proprietary software.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10271320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Adoption ==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10271330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Free software played a part in the development of the Internet, the World Wide Web and the infrastructure of [[dot-com companies]].@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10271340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Free software allows users to cooperate in enhancing and refining the programs they use; free software is a [[pure public good]] rather than a [[private good]].@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10271350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Companies that contribute to free software can increase commercial [[innovation]] amidst the void of [[patent]] [[cross licensing]] lawsuits.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10271360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(See [[Mpeg2#Patent holders|mpeg2 patent holders]])@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10271370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Under the free software business model, free software vendors may charge a fee for distribution and offer pay support and software customization services.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10271380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Proprietary software uses a different business model, where a customer of the proprietary software pays a fee for a license to use the software.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10271390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This license may grant the customer the ability to configure some or no parts of the software themselves.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10271400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Often some level of support is included in the purchase of proprietary software, but additional support services (especially for enterprise applications) are usually available for an additional fee.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10271410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some proprietary software vendors will also customize software for a fee.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10271420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Free software is generally available at little to no cost and can result in permanently lower costs compared to [[proprietary software]].@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10271430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@With free software, businesses can fit software to their specific needs by changing the software themselves or by hiring programmers to modify it for them.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10271440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Free software often has no warranty, and more importantly, generally does not assign legal liability to anyone.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10271450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, warranties are permitted between any two parties upon the condition of the software and its usage.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10271460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Such an agreement is made separately from the free software license.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10271470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Controversies ==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10271480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Binary blobs ===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10271490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In 2006, [[OpenBSD]] started the first campaign against the use of [[binary blobs]], in [[kernel (computer science)|kernels]].@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10271500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Blobs are usually freely distributable [[device driver]]s for hardware from vendors that do not reveal driver source code to users or developers.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10271510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This restricts the users' freedom to effectively modify the software and distribute modified versions.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10271520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Also, since the blobs are undocumented and may have [[computer bug|bugs]], they pose a security risk to any [[operating system]] whose kernel includes them.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10271530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The proclaimed aim of the campaign against blobs is to collect hardware documentation that allows developers to write free software drivers for that hardware, ultimately enabling all free operating systems to become or remain blob-free.@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10271540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The issue of binary blobs in the [[Linux kernel]] and other device drivers motivated some developers in Ireland to launch [[gNewSense]], a GNU/Linux distribution with all the binary blobs removed.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
